The paper focuses on the automatic analysis of affective behavior, which involves computer vision and machine learning techniques for tasks such as valence-arousal estimation, expression recognition, and action unit detection. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is the most likely sub-category. Additionally, cs.MM (Multimedia), cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction), cs.LG (Machine Learning), and cs.IR (Information Retrieval) are also possible sub-categories, as they are related to the use of multimedia data, user interaction, learning algorithms, and information retrieval techniques in affective computing.
